fields.title: Marvel will be forever
fields.snippet: Marvel Entertainment, LLC is an American entertainment company founded in June 1998 and based in New York City, New York, formed by the merger of Marvel Entertainment Group and Toy Biz.
fields.body:
Marvel Entertainment, LLC (formerly Marvel Enterprises) is an American entertainment company founded in June 1998 and based in New York City, New York, formed by the merger of Marvel Entertainment Group and Toy Biz. The company is a wholly owned subsidiary of The Walt Disney Company since 2009, and is mainly known for its comic books by Marvel Comics, as well as its forays into films and television/streaming shows, including those within the Marvel Cinematic Universe (MCU).

In 2009, The Walt Disney Company acquired Marvel Entertainment for US$4 billion;[1] it has been a limited liability company (LLC) since then. For financial reporting purposes, Marvel is primarily reported as part of Disney's Consumer Products segment ever since Marvel Studios' reorganization from Marvel Entertainment into Walt Disney Studios.[2]

Over the years, Marvel Entertainment has entered into several partnerships and negotiations with other companies across a variety of businesses. As of 2019, Marvel has film licensing agreements with Sony Pictures via Columbia Pictures (for Spider-Man films) and Universal Pictures (a right of first refusal to pick up the distribution rights to any future Hulk films produced by Marvel Studios), and theme park licensing agreements with IMG Worlds of Adventure and Universal Destinations & Experiences (for specific Marvel character rights at Islands of Adventure and Universal Studios Japan).[3] Aside from their contract with Universal Parks & Resorts, Marvel's characters and properties have also appeared at Disney Parks.[4]

fields.title: how to delete last commit
fields.snippet: To delete the last commit from your local repository and also update the working directory to match the latest commit, you can use the git reset command with the --hard option.
fields.body:
To delete the last commit from your local repository and also update the working directory to match the latest commit, you can use the `git reset` command with the `--hard` option. 

Here are the steps:

1. Open your terminal or Git Bash and navigate to the local repository where you want to delete the last commit.

2. Type the following command and press Enter:
   
   ```
   git reset --hard HEAD~1
   ```
   
   This command will delete the last commit and all changes that were made in it. If you want to delete more than one commit, change the number `1` to the number of commits you want to delete.
   
3. Type the following command and press Enter:

   ```
   git push --force
   ```
   
   This command will force push the changes to the remote repository.

Note: Be careful when using `git reset` as it can permanently delete commits and changes from your repository. Make sure you have a backup or are aware of the changes you are making before executing these commands.

fields.title: how to make a new branch and commit in it
fields.snippet: To create a new branch and commit changes to it, follow these steps:
fields.body:
To create a new branch and commit changes to it, follow these steps:

1. Open your terminal or Git Bash and navigate to your local repository.

2. Create a new branch using the following command:
   ```
   git branch new-branch-name
   ```
   Replace "new-branch-name" with the name you want to give to the new branch.

3. Switch to the new branch using the following command:
   ```
   git checkout new-branch-name
   ```
   
   Alternatively, you can create and switch to a new branch in one command by using the `-b` option:
   
   ```
   git checkout -b new-branch-name
   ```

4. Make changes to the files in your working directory.

5. Add the changes you made using the following command:
   ```
   git add .
   ```
   This command stages all changes for the next commit. If you only want to stage specific files, replace `.` with the filenames.

6. Commit the changes using the following command:
   ```
   git commit -m "commit message"
   ```
   Replace "commit message" with a brief description of the changes you made.

7. Push the changes to the remote repository using the following command:
   ```
   git push -u origin new-branch-name
   ```
   Replace "new-branch-name" with the name of the branch you created.

Congratulations! You have now created a new branch and committed changes to it.
